## 🏢 Intended Workflow or Task

- **Trigger:** New script or episode brief received from director or production coordinator
- **Actor:** Background art supervisor reviews and approves extracted location list
- **Timing:** Runs at the very start of production — before any creative work begins
- **Next step:** Output feeds directly into P02 (Workload Prioritisation)
```
Director sends script
      ↓
[P01 RUNS — extracts all background locations]
      ↓
Supervisor reviews and approves location list
      ↓
List passed to P02 for prioritisation
```

---

## ❗ Problem Being Solved

Background supervisors currently spend 45–90 minutes per episode manually reading through scripts and extracting location requirements into spreadsheets. This process is inconsistent — different supervisors capture different levels of detail, and locations implied in dialogue rather than stated explicitly are frequently missed. When briefs are incomplete, artists either pause work to ask questions or proceed with wrong assumptions, both of which create costly revision cycles later in production. On a mid-size studio producing 10–13 episodes per season, this represents an estimated 8–20 hours of avoidable supervisor time per season on brief extraction alone.

**Pain points addressed:**
- Locations missed when buried in dialogue or action lines
- Mood and atmosphere inconsistently captured across supervisors
- New artists unable to independently interpret vague script directions
- No standardised format across the department

---

## ⚡ Automation Potential

**Level:** High

| Dimension | Assessment |
|-----------|------------|
| Repetitiveness | Every episode and every script revision triggers this task |
| Data availability | Script documents readily available from production coordinator |
| Human judgment needed | Supervisor confirms complexity ratings and flags before sign-off |
| Integration possibility | Output could feed into a production tracking system (e.g. Shotgrid, Notion) |
| Estimated time saving | ~75% — from 45–90 min to 10–15 min per episode |

**Human-in-the-loop role:** Supervisor reviews AI-extracted location list, confirms complexity ratings, and approves before passing to P02. AI does not assign work — it prepares the information for human decision-making.

---

## ⚠️ Risks and Limitations

| Risk | Level | Mitigation |
|------|-------|------------|
| AI misreads implied locations not explicitly named in script | Medium | Prompt instructs AI to flag unclear or missing background requirements |
| Mood and atmosphere hallucinated where not stated in script | Medium | Prompt uses "if specified or implied" — uncertain fields are flagged rather than assumed |
| Complexity rating inaccurate without visual storyboard reference | Medium | Human supervisor confirms all complexity ratings before list enters P02 |
| Long scripts may produce inconsistent extraction quality | Low | Process script in scene blocks rather than full episode at once |

**Overall risk rating:** MEDIUM — outputs are always reviewed by a human supervisor before entering the pipeline, limiting downstream impact of any extraction errors.

